node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 01, 2021. May be a closeup.

node.text:
Photo by @bertiegregory / This Atlantic puffin's bill is packed full of sand eels. Puffins breed on land but fish at sea, so being able to carry multiple prey at once is key to efficiently—and therefore successfully—raising a puffling (puffin chick). The busy summer breeding colonies have now emptied out, and the puffins will spend the rest of the year at sea. Next spring the adults will return to land to start the whole process again. Meanwhile, the pufflings will stay at sea for three to five years before returning to land to raise their own chicks. 
Follow @bertiegregory for more wildlife adventures! #puffin #britishwildlife #cute #fishing #wildlifephotography

node.text: Photo by @taylorglenn // A pair of bison—icons of Jackson Hole, Wyoming—graze on Antelope Flats in Grand Teton National Park. I am lucky to call this incredible place home, but the wildlife here are the true locals. I made this image from a safe distance to give the bison the space they needed. Always keep a minimum distance of 25 yards between yourself and wildlife (and over a hundred yards for predators). It’s easy to forget that we are visitors to their home. We must be mindful of their best interest, especially when we want to get that perfect photo. // As you @visitjacksonhole you can help preserve the spirit of this special place when you live by #TheWildRules

Parthenon temple in the background. For more photos and videos from different parts of the world, follow me @mmuheisen and @mmuheisenpublic. #muhammedmuheisen #acropolis #Athens #Greece

node.text:
Photo by Prasenjeet Yadav @prasen.yadav / As I walked across my first jing kieng jri, or living root bridge, in Meghalaya, India, my mind darted this way and that, trying to find a comparable experience. No, it did not feel like crossing a concrete bridge. No, it did not feel like climbing a tree. Instead, it felt like a fairy tale come to life. And perhaps, in a way, that's what it is.
In a place where concrete bridges are unlikely to survive even a few decades because of earthquakes, landslides, and floods, these bridges grow stronger, more robust, and resilient with age. They do not require revenue to build—only time. The root bridges don't just support the humans who cross over them. Studies suggest that a single F. elastica tree can potentially support up to a few hundred living species including birds, insects, sometimes mammals, and vegetation like moss. The trees themselves are ecosystems, constantly interacting with their living and nonliving surroundings.

node.text: Photo by Luján Agusti @lujanag / Mount Olivia, the highest peak in the surroundings of Ushuaia, Argentina, is in the mountain range that borders the north of the city. The mountain has become a symbol of our city. Many visitors and locals climb it since it has four different routes of ascent, all of considerable difficulty. Follow me @lujanag to learn more about my life and work on the southern island of Tierra del Fuego.

node.text: Photo by @MichaelGeorge / The dichotomy of cold, pouring rain and a natural hot spring makes for a surprise delight in the pools at Nayara Gardens in Costa Rica. After a few minutes of light rain, a downpour opened up, leading us to use giant leaves as shelter. Once the lightning and thunder kicked in, it was time to make a run for it back under a proper roof. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #hotsprings #summerrain #downpour #nayaragardens #costarica

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 31, 2021. May be an image of nature and palm trees.

node.text:
Photo by @CarltonWard / The sun rises through a winter fog near Chassahowitzka National Wildlife Refuge on Florida's Gulf Coast. I paddled here during the Florida Wildlife Corridor Glades to Gulf Expedition in 2015. This 70-day, 1,000-mile trek, supported in part by @insidenatgeo, helped build the campaign to identify and conserve the Florida Wildlife Corridor, an 18-million-acre network of public conservation lands and private working lands that provides connected habitat for wide-ranging wildlife like the Florida panther. Earlier this year, the Florida legislature officially recognized the landscape through the Florida Wildlife Corridor Act and allocated $300 million for its conservation. 
To learn more, please follow @carltonward and @pathofthepanther. The Path of the Panther project, working to inspire the protection of the Florida Wildlife Corridor, is supported by the National Geographic Society.

node.text: Photo by @krystlejwright / Considered one of the most spectacular hikes in Western Australia, the Spider Walk in Karijini National Park's Hancock Gorge weaves among the ancient landscape. Generally there are two types of hikers you'll see: either those who are bone-dry or those completely submerged in the icy waters.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 30, 2021. May be an image of bird and nature.

node.text:
Photo by @joshuacogan / Birds take flight below a fading moon during an early morning at the southern tip of Lake Michigan. While driving across the country with the family last year, it was these dawn hours that gave me some time to myself before the rest of the crew awoke. Even here in the flatlands, there was magic to be found. 
For more journeys inward and outward, follow me @joshuacogan.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on August 30, 2021. May be an image of one or more people.

node.text: Photo by Robbie Shone @shonephoto / During the Greenland Caves Project's 2019 expedition, we explored Kate’s Cove cave as far as we could. We went down a steep boulder pile into the depths of the cave. The floor was strewn with rocks and the walls were cold. We had never been in a cave before where the rocks were so cold. The expedition medic even suggested I had frostnip at one point! After about 80 meters (262 feet), the bouldery floor gave way to a narrow slot. Pictured here, Chris bridges his way over the top of the slot. We climbed down to see if it led to a way on. It got colder and colder, and at its deepest point it was minus 17.1°C (1.2°F). Could this be one of the coldest caves in the world? Who knows.
